1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:25,000
 So, thanks again. And what I would like to share with you is a proposal, because digging into the Greek fathers, most of all the Cappadocians, and the fathers that addressed the pneumatonic crisis in the second half of the first century,

2
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:39,000
 I've discovered something that I think could be very useful to rethink the Filioque discussion in our days when we are far from the issues that caused the division,

3
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:47,000
 also from the political outcomes of some bad things that the Western did against the Eastern, and so on.

4
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:59,000
 So, maybe going back to the sources, we can find a common ground to overcome something that is completely crazy, that is the division among the Christians.

5
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:09,000
 So, most of all, we cannot be divided in the name of the Holy Spirit. So, this is completely crazy, and we are used to that, but it's wrong,

6
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:28,000
 if we believe in what we believe, in what we say to believe. So, for this, the first point, the starting point, should be, in my opinion, a change in our approach, in our view, in our epistemology.

7
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:38,000
 Because we are not working on something that is like an equation, like the solution to a mathematical problem.

8
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:51,000
 We have a metaphysical view from the Bible, where God is infinite and transcendent, while the world is finite and temporal.

9
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:58,000
 This is completely different with respect to what happened with Aristotle, Plato, and so on in classical Greek metaphysics.

10
00:01:58,000 --> 00:02:08,000
 So, according to the ancient Greek, the solution of the theological problem were related to mathematics.

11
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:11,000
 Let's think about the Pythagorean tradition.

12
00:02:11,000 --> 00:02:20,000
 In our case, the only way to get to know God is through personal relationships, because God is infinite,

13
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:30,000
 and only the incarnation of the Logos, who were listening before, of Nysia, made it possible for us to see this new logic,

14
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:38,000
 that is the logic according to which the world was made, that is one plus one plus one equals three, or one.

15
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:45,000
 So, this is new, this is not something, it's not something absurd, it's something real,

16
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:50,000
 that we should learn through the Gospel, through the Church, and so on.

17
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:58,000
 According to Gregor of Nysia, for example, we should be very, always very conscious when we talk about God,

18
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:08,000
 because our images of him could become idols, because we always use words that come from creation.

19
00:03:08,000 --> 00:03:16,000
 So, if you're not very careful, we can project something of the finite world onto God,

20
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:22,000
 and lose, miss the real gifts that we receive through the revelation.

21
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:29,000
 And I try to develop this in one book that is Rethinking the Filioque published by Erdemans,

22
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:41,000
 but in really, the stuff that is behind the book is in another book that is published by Cambridge University Press,

23
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:48,000
 almost in the same time, because the Cappadocian reshaped classical metaphysics,

24
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:52,000
 and because of that reshaped classical epistemology.

25
00:03:52,000 --> 00:04:03,000
 And the problem of the Filioque, in my view, is related to the fact that in the Middle Ages, we lost this approach.

26
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:11,000
 Because of that, the fathers in the first 9th century were in communion with the fathers in the East and the West,

27
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:13,000
 were in perfect communion.

28
00:04:13,000 --> 00:04:18,000
 They knew about the different traditions, but they were not scandalized.

29
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:23,000
 And also, looking at the history of Dhamma can help us a lot,

30
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:28,000
 because we are used to formula when we talk about nematology, about the Trinity.

31
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:38,000
 But if we look, for example, at origin, we can see how his reading of the Bible used different models.

32
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:40,000
 The first one was more Jewish.

33
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:52,000
 And because of that, for example, in his opinion, one of the first attempts that he tried was that the Father, God is the Father,

34
00:04:52,000 --> 00:05:02,000
 and the Son and the Holy Spirit are like two carubs, like two archangels that are united with the Father.

35
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:06,000
 So this is a sort of triangular model.

36
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:18,000
 And that another approach was, for example, commenting the fact that Jesus liked the child and wanted the apostles to leave,

37
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:21,000
 to let the child come towards him.

38
00:05:21,000 --> 00:05:27,000
 And Origen commented something that disappeared in the following years of Jesus, and it's quite apparent why it happened.

39
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:31,000
 So he identified this child with the Holy Spirit.

40
00:05:31,000 --> 00:05:40,000
 It's again this sort of model where, in some sense, the Son and the Holy Spirit are parallel, just below the Father.

41
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:41,000
 This is more Jewish.

42
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:52,000
 And the problem was that, according to Origen, some dogmatical solutions were not developed.

43
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:57,000
 He had to think, for the first time, how to express something.

44
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:05,000
 And also, if you read Bayesian, for example, his command, he is the Spiritus Santo on the Holy Spirit.

45
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:11,000
 He distinguishes between dogma and proclamation and kerygma.

46
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:17,000
 And he says that the dogma is for few people, for people thinking about the truth.

47
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:20,000
 So this is also really important.

48
00:06:20,000 --> 00:06:29,000
 So Origen had developed some ways of expressing the mystery that was believed from the beginning.

49
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:36,000
 The martyrs were dying for the mystery for the God of Jesus Christ, who was Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.

50
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:39,000
 They were baptized in the name of the Father, the Son of the Holy Spirit.

51
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:44,000
 But how to explain that the Son is not the Father, but is one with him?

52
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:49,000
 How to explain that the Son and the Holy Spirit are two different persons, but are one substance?

53
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:52,000
 That was, that required some thinking.

54
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:58,000
 And the solution that Origen discovered, you have the text, the references, and so on.

55
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:02,000
 Also, I can share, if you want, I can send the presentation.

56
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:13,000
 The solution that Origen tried was that, in some sense, the Father has power on everything.

57
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:21,000
 On the contrary, the Son has a limited power on rational beings, and the Holy Spirit also is in charge of sanctification.

58
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:28,000
 So it works only for spiritual beings who are in communion with God.

59
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:41,000
 So for him, the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit were purely spiritual, and that was the difference with respect to every created being, because even the angels were created with a light body.

60
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:53,000
 But to express the difference between how to distinguish the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit was in some sense not perfect in origin, because it was achieved through participation.

61
00:07:53,000 --> 00:08:02,000
 So the idea is that the Son is not the good, the being, the truth, but just participates, part of the good, part of the being.

62
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:03,000
 And this is reflected in action.

63
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:17,000
 So he successfully reshaped the metaphysical framework, because Origen is working with an infinite God and a finite world.

64
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:36,000
 On the side of eternity, it's more complex, because he has the eons, and also this is reflected in the Nicene crisis, because the idea of a generation of the Son before times is related to this interpretation of Origen.

65
00:08:36,000 --> 00:09:03,000
 But what is really important in Origen and in the following Fathers was that they developed something new with respect to classical metaphysics and enlarging, broadening metaphysics, because they developed a sort of ontology, not in the sense of Heidegger, but as a logos about being, where metaphysics was just the foundation of the physics, so the cosmic reality.

66
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:21,000
 According to Origen, Athanasius, the Cappadocians, on the contrary, when we think about God, we can think about being, and we have to accept a gap between God himself, who is infinite and eternal, and the world who is finite and temporal.

67
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:35,000
 And because of that, we should always stay in the perspective of apophaticism, because we cannot control conceptually God, he is always beyond our ability to express him.

68
00:09:35,000 --> 00:10:03,760
 And what happened in the first part of the fourth century, in my opinion, was that the fathers, starting from Athanasius, had to express the fact that the logos is not in between the father and the world, is not the thought of the father conceived in order to create the world, but it's fully within the divine substance.

69
00:10:03,760 --> 00:10:22,760
 So it's fully eternal, and this meant that the distinction between the father and the son should be expressed in a new way, because according to classical metaphysics, the identification process was related to substances.

70
00:10:22,760 --> 00:10:31,360
 So, to be different, if the father and the father and the father and the father and the son are different, according to Aristotle, that meant that they are two different substances.

71
00:10:31,360 --> 00:10:37,260
 On the contrary, according to the gospel, they are one, one thing, one substance, divine and eternal.

72
00:10:37,260 --> 00:10:47,300
 And so, the very biblical names, the new testamentary names, suggested relationship as a way to express the difference.

73
00:10:47,300 --> 00:10:56,980
 So, the father is one with the son, but it's not the son, because the relationship that the father has with the son is fatherhood.

74
00:10:56,980 --> 00:11:00,180
 On the contrary, the son is a sonship.

75
00:11:00,180 --> 00:11:11,200
 And the problem of the second part of the first century was to express, to do the same, to express how the Holy Spirit is different with respect to the father and the son.

76
00:11:11,720 --> 00:11:18,140
 And the Neumatomachians attacked exactly on this side.

77
00:11:18,140 --> 00:11:33,240
 And what they had to achieve in the second part of the fourth century was to move the pneuma from a mediation figure to the divine immanence,

78
00:11:33,240 --> 00:11:40,320
 completing, in some sense, the identities of the three divine persons in a relational way.

79
00:11:40,320 --> 00:11:51,760
 So, the father is father, through his generation of the son, and also through the relationship with the pneuma, with the Holy Spirit.

80
00:11:51,760 --> 00:11:56,860
 And vice versa, mutually, all the three identities are co-relation.

81
00:11:56,860 --> 00:12:02,020
 And this was achieved, in my opinion, according to what I found by the Cappadocians.

82
00:12:02,380 --> 00:12:15,780
 But even before the tension was present, this is a wonderful text by Eusebius, where, in some sense, he is pushing, in his dialogue with Marcellus,

83
00:12:15,780 --> 00:12:19,340
 he is pushing the interpretations that were available at the time.

84
00:12:19,440 --> 00:12:45,540
 So, there is a tension here between a Porewetai and John 16, 14.

85
00:12:45,540 --> 00:12:50,440
 This was present at the beginning of the first century.

86
00:12:50,440 --> 00:13:01,940
 Athanasius, with his genius that is incredible, would be able to express also the criticism of the Neumatomachians,

87
00:13:01,940 --> 00:13:08,080
 who, in a nutshell, said they were, in my opinion, literalist.

88
00:13:09,080 --> 00:13:11,580
 So, their exegesis was literalist.

89
00:13:11,580 --> 00:13:16,600
 And they said, it's written nowhere that the Holy Spirit is God.

90
00:13:16,600 --> 00:13:19,140
 It's written nowhere that the Holy Spirit creates.

91
00:13:19,140 --> 00:13:21,560
 On the contrary, we know that the Logos creates.

92
00:13:22,840 --> 00:13:33,740
 And if it were true that the Holy Spirit is God, this means that the Logos has a brother, but he is not the only begotten in this way.

93
00:13:33,740 --> 00:13:38,700
 Either that the father is the grandfather of the Holy Spirit.

94
00:13:38,700 --> 00:13:46,660
 This was the acquisition that Athanasius had to fight against.

95
00:13:47,440 --> 00:13:51,160
 And his solution was, in some sense, very simple and effective.

96
00:13:51,160 --> 00:13:58,660
 The father has a relationship with the son that does correspond with the relationship the son has with the Holy Spirit.

97
00:13:58,660 --> 00:14:05,920
 So, just because the son is one thing with the father, the Holy Spirit should be one thing with the son and the Holy Spirit.

98
00:14:05,980 --> 00:14:07,800
 Because their relationship is the same.

99
00:14:07,800 --> 00:14:13,320
 But, also, this is the weak point, the blind spot of Athanasius.

100
00:14:13,320 --> 00:14:27,280
 Because he was able to distinguish numerically the two processions, but wasn't able to express how the procession of the Holy Spirit is different, but related to generation.

101
00:14:27,280 --> 00:14:28,720
 This was the point.

102
00:14:29,560 --> 00:14:40,940
 But, everything that was developed by Basil and Gregory of Nyssa, Gregory of Nyssa, in my opinion, was already present in Athanasius' neumatology.

103
00:14:40,940 --> 00:14:45,000
 For example, this text is incredible and it's worth being read.

104
00:14:45,220 --> 00:14:53,420
 For by the same will with which the son is willed by the father, he himself loves, honors, and wills the father.

105
00:14:53,420 --> 00:14:58,380
 Therefore, the will that belongs to the father is also one in the son.

106
00:14:58,380 --> 00:15:02,820
 So that from this, we can contemplate the son in the father and the son.

107
00:15:02,820 --> 00:15:03,960
 And the father in the son.

108
00:15:04,500 --> 00:15:07,840
 In the end, there's a commentary on John 10, 30.

109
00:15:07,840 --> 00:15:13,220
 But he's speaking about will in the divine substance.

110
00:15:13,220 --> 00:15:21,440
 This is very daring because we know that Arians were stressing that the son came from the father's will.

111
00:15:21,560 --> 00:15:28,180
 But in the end, Athanasius is saying, the father wills the son in generation.

112
00:15:28,180 --> 00:15:30,920
 It's an act of love, not just an act of knowledge.

113
00:15:30,920 --> 00:15:33,340
 It's knowledge and self-gift.

114
00:15:33,340 --> 00:15:37,980
 And the son is the image of the father because he gives back everything.

115
00:15:37,980 --> 00:15:40,380
 So he wills the father.

116
00:15:40,380 --> 00:15:43,700
 And this is beautiful because this is correlational.

117
00:15:44,700 --> 00:15:54,180
 And in some sense, what we got in the second half of the fourth century was a development of this approach.

118
00:15:54,180 --> 00:16:06,420
 We have also wonderful, wonderful text by Epiphanius, also witnessing to the role of the son in the procession of the Holy Spirit.

119
00:16:06,420 --> 00:16:23,500
 Because if we go back to the text by Athanasius, we can see how if we read the Holy Spirit as the will of the love, of the mutual gift of the son and the father,

120
00:16:23,500 --> 00:16:28,980
 we can see how a filioque into brackets can be read here.

121
00:16:29,660 --> 00:16:41,560
 And what Epiphanius was doing was, in some sense, taking advantage of John 16, 14, to distinguish a porewetai,

122
00:16:41,560 --> 00:16:46,260
 that is the coming of the Holy Spirit, just from the father as the first source,

123
00:16:46,260 --> 00:16:53,320
 what Augustine calls principaliter, the procession principaliter.

124
00:16:53,680 --> 00:17:04,540
 And the fact that the Holy Spirit takes from the son, that means that what is given back to the father goes through the son,

125
00:17:04,540 --> 00:17:09,820
 at least relationally, not in a causal way, but in a relational way.

126
00:17:09,820 --> 00:17:16,180
 And his explication, his way of expressing this is very interesting.

127
00:17:16,180 --> 00:17:21,500
 Also, from the last line, you can see how it's just reading Nicaea.

128
00:17:21,500 --> 00:17:27,220
 True life from true light is a reference to, an apparent reference to Nicaea.

129
00:17:27,220 --> 00:17:34,020
 With Gregory of Nyssa, we have a terrific contribution, a very important contribution, in my opinion,

130
00:17:34,720 --> 00:17:41,400
 because he expressed the fact that the father engenders the son,

131
00:17:41,400 --> 00:17:47,060
 saying that the son is king just as the father is king,

132
00:17:47,060 --> 00:17:52,440
 because he receives the kingship, so the power of the king,

133
00:17:52,440 --> 00:17:58,220
 and gives back this power that is living, substantial and subsisting kingdom.

134
00:17:58,220 --> 00:18:02,360
 And this power is the Holy Spirit.

135
00:18:02,360 --> 00:18:09,320
 So, just as Athanasius was expressing this willing with a gift back,

136
00:18:09,320 --> 00:18:15,020
 Gregory of Nyssa could express this in terms of kingship, royal power,

137
00:18:15,020 --> 00:18:19,420
 and also as exchange of glory.

138
00:18:19,420 --> 00:18:26,020
 So, in the same way, Gregory said that the father engenders the son,

139
00:18:26,020 --> 00:18:28,980
 giving his glory, his own glory, as kabod,

140
00:18:29,420 --> 00:18:33,580
 and not as in the Greek way, but in the Jewish way.

141
00:18:33,580 --> 00:18:36,660
 So, the weight of God to the son.

142
00:18:36,660 --> 00:18:40,780
 And the son gives back this being, true being,

143
00:18:40,780 --> 00:18:44,460
 not just part of being, but full being to the father.

144
00:18:44,460 --> 00:18:50,820
 In Adab Labium, that is a very powerful work by Gregory of Nyssa,

145
00:18:51,480 --> 00:18:59,540
 also we can see how he expresses the fact that the distinction between what comes from the father

146
00:18:59,540 --> 00:19:04,680
 immediately, directly, and what comes from the father through the son

147
00:19:04,680 --> 00:19:07,580
 is imminent, and not just economical.

148
00:19:07,580 --> 00:19:16,940
 And this is quite evident in the commentary on the song of the son.

149
00:19:16,940 --> 00:19:23,860
 We have the same expression, also with the idea that the Holy Spirit is the

150
00:19:23,860 --> 00:19:27,720
 sundetic course between the father and the son.

151
00:19:28,220 --> 00:19:33,280
 And this idea is present also in Gregory and Nazianzen, I'm almost done, almost finishing,

152
00:19:33,280 --> 00:19:40,100
 because it was a common strategy in answering, in responding to the nematomeca.

153
00:19:40,100 --> 00:19:46,540
 So, the idea was to, because they accepted that the son and the father are God, are one God.

154
00:19:46,540 --> 00:19:53,660
 So, the idea of the Cappadocia was to insert the Holy Spirit between the father and the son,

155
00:19:53,660 --> 00:19:57,520
 without violating the taxes, the order.

156
00:19:57,520 --> 00:20:03,700
 And so, for example, in this text by Gregory of Nazianzus, we can see that in the procession

157
00:20:03,700 --> 00:20:09,000
 from the father, the spirit is not a creature, in that it's not begotten, it's not the son,

158
00:20:09,000 --> 00:20:15,020
 in that it stands in the middle, meson, between the one who is unbegotten, the one who begets,

159
00:20:15,020 --> 00:20:16,160
 he is God.

160
00:20:16,160 --> 00:20:22,860
 So, we can see how the Holy Spirit is God because he's in between, relationally, not causally.

161
00:20:23,660 --> 00:20:29,880
 And in the same sense, the distinction is relational through schesis.

162
00:20:29,880 --> 00:20:33,520
 And in this second text, we can see the same.

163
00:20:33,520 --> 00:20:38,240
 What is it, then, that the spirit lacks, they say, in order to be the son?

164
00:20:38,240 --> 00:20:40,860
 For it lacks nothing, it will be the son.

165
00:20:40,860 --> 00:20:45,060
 We say that it lacks nothing, for God is not incomplete.

166
00:20:45,060 --> 00:20:47,180
 The difference consists in the manifestation.

167
00:20:47,400 --> 00:20:49,720
 But this manifestation is not economical.

168
00:20:49,720 --> 00:20:52,920
 This ecfansis is not economical.

169
00:20:52,920 --> 00:20:57,420
 And we can see why, so to speak, in the mutual relation.

170
00:20:57,420 --> 00:21:01,520
 And because of that, there is a difference of the names.

171
00:21:01,520 --> 00:21:02,920
 And the names are immanent.

172
00:21:03,400 --> 00:21:13,760
 If we would read this text by Gregory Nassant, saying that the relational distinction is just an economical dimension,

173
00:21:13,760 --> 00:21:20,860
 we would deny that the names of the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit are the names of the divine person in the immanence.

174
00:21:21,540 --> 00:21:30,500
 And also, in this text, we can see how this approach, this relational reading of the immanence of the Trinity,

175
00:21:30,500 --> 00:21:37,860
 is the approach of the epistemology of the fathers, the Cappadocian fathers, who were apophatic.

176
00:21:38,360 --> 00:21:46,620
 So, in this sense, for example, according to Gregory Nassant, the true theologian is not the one who understands everything.

177
00:21:46,620 --> 00:21:54,220
 The best theologian is not the he who has understood everything, because the finite cannot contain the infinite.

178
00:21:54,220 --> 00:22:03,960
 But he's the one who can imagine more gathering the traces, gathering what the shadows of the mystery cast on us.

179
00:22:04,140 --> 00:22:15,440
 And also, we know that in 410, in Seleucia, when the Syriac could meet, the bishop Syriac could meet after persecution,

180
00:22:15,440 --> 00:22:22,440
 they received the Nicene Creed, and in the nomatological article, they added a filioque,

181
00:22:22,440 --> 00:22:26,820
 saying that the Holy Spirit is from the Father and the Son.

182
00:22:28,160 --> 00:22:34,680
 And this is really interesting, in my opinion, because there is an implicit, even in the Greek,

183
00:22:34,680 --> 00:22:42,720
 that is this relational and not causal coming of the Holy Spirit through the Son,

184
00:22:42,720 --> 00:22:46,260
 that is present also in other traditions.

185
00:22:46,420 --> 00:22:59,740
 And talking with Michel Stavroux, he read my results as coherent with what Blemides developed centuries later.

186
00:22:59,740 --> 00:23:07,520
 So, this for me was a confirmation that what I was reading was a Byzantine confirmation of my reading

187
00:23:07,520 --> 00:23:12,920
 that is not just Western and not try to augustinize the Cappadocian.

188
00:23:12,920 --> 00:23:15,580
 It's something that is present in the Eastern tradition itself.

189
00:23:15,580 --> 00:23:23,980
 The summary is that Origin had two possibilities in explaining the Trinity.

190
00:23:23,980 --> 00:23:29,600
 The normal one, the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit, a linear model,

191
00:23:30,460 --> 00:23:33,680
 that is what we are used to, but also a triangular model.

192
00:23:33,680 --> 00:23:41,780
 In some sense, the clash about the position of the Son and the procession of the Holy Spirit

193
00:23:41,780 --> 00:23:44,980
 are the result of the conflict between these two models.

194
00:23:44,980 --> 00:23:47,720
 No model can be perfect.

195
00:23:47,720 --> 00:23:49,700
 Every model is a way of expressing it.

196
00:23:49,700 --> 00:23:51,120
 The mystery is always beyond.

197
00:23:51,120 --> 00:23:53,660
 Athanasius found a wonderful solution,

198
00:23:53,920 --> 00:23:58,080
 but he was exposed to the criticism of the pneumatomachians

199
00:23:58,080 --> 00:24:01,280
 because he distinguished the two processions numerically

200
00:24:01,280 --> 00:24:06,340
 but couldn't express perfectly how the procession of the Spirit

201
00:24:06,340 --> 00:24:07,900
 is different with respect to generation.

202
00:24:07,900 --> 00:24:11,480
 And through Epiphanius and the Cappadocian,

203
00:24:11,480 --> 00:24:15,380
 we got to a solution where the position of the Holy Spirit

204
00:24:15,380 --> 00:24:20,300
 is the third because of the taxes he preserved,

205
00:24:20,300 --> 00:24:24,740
 but also relationally is connected to both the Father and the Son.

206
00:24:24,740 --> 00:24:29,840
 So my proposal is that in their response to the pneumatomachians,

207
00:24:29,840 --> 00:24:32,900
 the Greek Father introduced an active role of the Son

208
00:24:32,900 --> 00:24:34,760
 in the procession of the Holy Spirit

209
00:24:34,760 --> 00:24:37,440
 and in the immanence of the divine substance.

210
00:24:37,440 --> 00:24:41,380
 This role is not causal because it's purely relational.

211
00:24:41,380 --> 00:24:46,720
 So this is completely different with respect to filioquism

212
00:24:46,720 --> 00:24:49,460
 in the Immunale with Ansel, nothing to do with Ansel.

213
00:24:49,460 --> 00:24:50,520
 This is something different.

214
00:24:50,520 --> 00:24:53,920
 This tradition maybe could be the foundation

215
00:24:53,920 --> 00:24:56,380
 for the development of the theology expressed

216
00:24:56,380 --> 00:24:58,500
 also in the West through the filioquism

217
00:24:58,500 --> 00:25:02,560
 before the Middle Ages.

218
00:25:02,560 --> 00:25:05,680
 So in my opinion, what Augustine meant

219
00:25:05,680 --> 00:25:08,080
 was this same theology.

220
00:25:09,080 --> 00:25:15,900
 What we could find in Hilarious in Tertullian himself so very early

221
00:25:15,900 --> 00:25:19,800
 is related to this side, this perspective.

222
00:25:19,800 --> 00:25:23,880
 And also, it's very important that the first eight centuries

223
00:25:23,880 --> 00:25:26,720
 presented no division on this.

224
00:25:26,720 --> 00:25:31,440
 So we can share the faith of the first seven councils

225
00:25:31,440 --> 00:25:33,000
 that define orthodoxy.

226
00:25:33,640 --> 00:25:37,680
 And because of that, maybe we could accept together

227
00:25:37,680 --> 00:25:39,680
 this version of the filioquism.

228
00:25:39,680 --> 00:25:44,120
 So what the fathers of the church of the first and ninth centuries

229
00:25:44,120 --> 00:25:47,460
 believed on the relationship with the Holy Spirit

230
00:25:47,460 --> 00:25:50,340
 and the Son in the procession, in the second procession.

231
00:25:50,340 --> 00:25:51,020
 Thanks a lot.

